    <p class="blue">Medical specialists have a specific name for what happens to the bladder when the prostate obstructs urinary flow long enough.</p>

    <p>They call it <strong>Trabeculation</strong> — or in plain terms, the "Leather Bladder."</p>

    <p>That's because your bladder is a muscle — flexible, elastic, built to fill and empty without effort.</p>

    <p>When a swollen prostate narrows the urethra, the bladder can't empty freely.</p>

    <p>So it compensates by pushing harder. Every single time.</p>

    <p>Night after night. Month after month.</p>

    <p>The wall begins to thicken — just like any overloaded muscle would.</p>

    <p>But in the bladder, this thickening triggers something that can't simply heal with rest.</p>

    <p class="blue">Collagen fibers begin depositing between the muscle layers.</p>

    <p>Bands of scar tissue weave into the bladder wall.</p>

    <p>The tissue stops being soft and pliable — and starts becoming stiff. Rigid. Leather-like.</p>

    <p>When functioning normally, your bladder can stretch, hold, and empty cleanly — supporting <strong>unbroken sleep and confident daily function.</strong></p>


    <h2>Why Your 'Leather Bladder' Gets Worse Over Time</h2>

    <!-- BLADDER WALL CROSS-SECTIONS GRID -->
    <div class="img-ph h300{% if section.settings.diagram_2 != blank %} has-image{% endif %}">
