    <p class="blue">Your age, the duration of the obstruction, and the level of prostate inflammation all accelerate this process.</p>

    <p>At first, you might notice <strong>urgency that hits before the bladder is actually full.</strong></p>

    <p>Then the trips get more frequent, especially at night.</p>

    <p>Soon there's that unsettling feeling of <strong>never quite emptying</strong> — you go, but the pressure barely lifts.</p>

    <p>Like a low-grade anxiety is now attached to every bathroom trip, every night, every long drive.</p>

    <p>But the final and most consequential stage is what urologists document in imaging:</p>

    <p>Once the bladder wall becomes significantly trabeculated, it can no longer hold urine properly, sense its own fullness accurately, or empty completely.</p>

    <p>This makes the urgency more insistent and more frequent — even as the actual volume becomes smaller.</p>

    <p>Which creates a vicious cycle:</p>

    <p>more straining means more collagen deposits, which means more stiffness, which means more urgency.</p>


