    <p>The bad news is that <strong>Trabeculation does not reverse on its own.</strong></p>

    <p>Once the collagen sets in, it stays.</p>

    <p>Even if you later treat the prostate — through medication, surgery, or any other means — the scar tissue in the bladder wall does not dissolve.</p>

    <p>The elasticity that's been lost doesn't come back.</p>

    <p class="blue">This means that without intervention, many men waiting for symptoms to get "bad enough" are steadily approaching a point of no return.</p>

    <p>And the worst part?</p>

    <p>Most solutions aimed at prostate symptoms — <strong>simply don't address this process at all.</strong></p>

    <p>They manage the urgency temporarily, while the obstruction continues and the bladder wall keeps thickening.</p>

    <p>It's like your car engine is overheating — and instead of fixing the engine, you keep adding coolant to buy time.</p>

    <p>You're just managing the overflow rather than stopping the <strong>underlying damage.</strong></p>


